       			<item>
				<guid>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52d2add069bedd1140b5455a</guid>
				<title>Ken Danagger</title>
				<pubDate>Sun, 12 Jan 2014 09:59:28 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52d2add069bedd1140b5455a</link>
				<description>Your argument for gold as a store of value:
&quot;If all else fails, you can make pretty things out of it&quot; - Great! Unfortunately that won't feed you, or keep you warm. If people won't trade real goods and services for it, it's useless. Granted, that is not likely to happen. Historically, it has NEVER happened. However, in our modern global economy, gold has a few drawbacks. Namely, lack of liquidity and transportability. Sure, you can trade paper or electronic promissory notes for gold, but then you have the same counter-party risk as fiat dollars. Even with the physical, you have debasement risk such as gold plated tungsten, etc.

Your argument for the USD as a store of value:
1) It is accepted by the gov't mob as &quot;protection money&quot; against being imprisoned. That isn't exactly what I'd call an attribute for a honest and fair currency. If given a choice, I think most people would choose to not use mobster money that the mob tracks every unit of so they can extract their &quot;cut&quot; by force.
2) The FED promises to &quot;buy them back&quot; - to intentionally deflate the money supply? AHHhhahah! Riiight. Propaganda. 
The FED can only do, and only does one thing now - INFLATE.
In theory the FED could try to reign in run-away inflation by drastically raising interest rates (as it did 35 years ago), but that trick will no longer work with our monstrous debt. The result would be a debt default - and the same destruction of the dollar end result.
The FED is powerless to do anything but further inflate now. It is trapped. The only thing keeping the inflation pressure cooker from exploding right now is our massive exports of USD around the world. There are clear signs that the USD is being increasingly rejected around world - and this will be the fuel for more war.

Back to bitcoin. What backs it? What makes it a reliable store of value? The answer is exactly the same as for gold or federal reserve promissory notes;

Consumer confidence and the productive capacity of the economy. 

That's it. Without a productive economy that produces the goods and services that people need, fiat paper, bitcoins, and gold are all worthless.
There is no debate that people worldwide are rapidly loosing confidence in paper promissory notes issued by criminal banksters and their gov't accomplices. This is nothing new however - all gov't fiat currencies eventually get abused and crash to zero.
Gold has historically been an outstanding as a store of value, but it is currently being crushed by the dilution of the paper markets.
Bitcoin can't be diluted because the algorithm itself prevents it. The entire decentralized network must agree on the addition of every new unit - and the limit is hard-coded at every node. You can try to tamper with a single node, or even a hundred nodes, or even a thousand nodes, but any efforts to circumvent the rules will be rejected by the overall network that exists globally - outside of the influence of government looters and criminals.

The utility of a currency as a reliable store of value basically comes down to public perception. Legal tender laws, world reserve currency status and propaganda have kept the USD at the forefront, but those tricks are failing. People are looking for a safe place to store their wealth that has the transaction utility that a modern digital global economy demands. The one that the free market chooses, will likely be the one that works best.
Further innovation and competition will keep things fluid. That is a very good thing. Bitcoin, nor any other form of currency should be forced upon people if something better, more secure, or more flexible comes along.</description>                            
			</item>
