       			<item>
				<guid>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c2777feab8ea982dc23ca4</guid>
				<title>Jonas Lihnell</title>
				<pubDate>Tue, 31 Dec 2013 02:51:27 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c2777feab8ea982dc23ca4</link>
				<description>The algorithms are calculating a proof of work to help build concensus between participants in the network regarding the validity of transactions. Each node verifies that the funds to be sent comes from a valid source and that the source has the permissions to send the fund and that the funds exists and are spendable.

The algorithms are calculating, in effect, verifications/validations of transactions.
The algortightms are doing this as a service to all other nodes in the network to help reach concensus about the validity of the transaction.

If you need a more detailed answer I recommend reading the original whitepaper, it explains things decenty and in great detail despite only being a couple of pages long.</description>                            
