       			<item>
				<guid>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c18db56da811a4601cf3e5</guid>
				<title>Rick Van Coevering</title>
				<pubDate>Mon, 30 Dec 2013 10:13:57 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c18db56da811a4601cf3e5</link>
				<description>The problem with Bitcoin, as with any other currency, is its acceptance and transferability. Bitcoins, like Reichsmarks have exactly the value of the goods and/or services that others are willing to trade for in exchange. When the Reichsmark became inflated you could not trade truckloads for a loaf of bread. Bitcoins may have a designed protection against inflation, but they give no guaranty for acceptance. It makes no difference if you have one or a thousand bitcoins if the seller wants dollars or euros. 
The risk of the bitcoin as currency is that it is becoming more and more the currency of criminals. As money laundering through bitcoin proliferates it looks to become increasing illicit in actual commerce. Someone may take your bitcoin, but only at a discount so that it can be fenced it and the seller can get real currency. And any bitcoin that you own may (will) be confiscated and/or criminalized by your particular sovereign. 
Compounding the problem with its lack of liquidity is bitcoins recent run on fraudulent exchanges wherein thousands of bitcoins have been stolen. If bitcoin cannot be reliably banked its value evaporates. 
The bitcoin of today is the tulip of the 17th century, except it is neither so pretty nor so fragrant.</description>                            
