				<pubDate>Sun, 29 Dec 2013 12:40:43 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c05e9becad04df0402ec55</link>
				<description>Well, you're correct that there are no limits on clones, and anyone is welcome to make their own copycat payment network. Bitcoin is really just a protocol, or standard, that people are voluntarily choosing to adopt. Bitcoin, though, has a number of advantages over any clone that you could create. These advantages include: First mover/Network effect, acceptance as payment, infrastructure (Bitcoin businesses, start ups, etc.), mining power (security against double spends), media attention, etc...

Thinking of another protocol, internet protocol, might be helpful. Anyone is welcome to create their own clone of internet protocol, but why hasn't this happened? Why aren't boat loads of people switching over to a new &quot;internet protocol&quot; every week? Partially for the above advantages, which apply equally to IP, and partially because clones provide no added value, or compelling reason to transition.

The *real* threat would be a new protocol, analogous to Bitcoin, that isn't a clone but rather provides real value above and beyond Bitcoin. Then people would have a compelling reason to switch over. Then again, the Bitcoin protocol could always just be modified at that point to incorporate whatever innovation this new &quot;coin&quot; brings with it. This seems most likely, considering the vested interest already in Bitcoin.</description>                            
