				<title>Nigel Hess</title>
				<pubDate>Sun, 29 Dec 2013 12:30:01 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c05c1969beddc64002ec64</link>
				<description>This goes back to the question of &quot;intrinsic value&quot; or utility. Gold has some obvious utility, outside of being a store of value, in both industry and as jewelry. Bitcoin has utility as a decentralized payment network. After all, Bitcoin is a new technology that enables arbitrary value to be sent anywhere in the world instantaneously, at near zero cost (zero friction), and with no point of failure or trusted third party. The utility here should be obvious. The fact that &quot;bitcoins&quot; can't be held in the palm of your hand, like physical gold, is irrelevant. 

Once you acknowledge that the Bitcoin protocol, as a payment network, has utility, and that the sole unit of account on this network is in the form of &quot;bitcoins&quot;, it shouldn't be surprising that they should command a legitimate market price, independent of pure speculation. Anything that is both useful and scarce will have a price.</description>                            
