				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c05710ecad04f47302ec5b</link>
				<description>This. As a transmission medium, it's digital copper, digital hydraulic oil. The more power you need to transmit, the more work you need your machine to do, the more coal you need to shift down the conveyor; then the more rubber belting, or hydraulic oil, or kWh of current you need, to do the job.

Looked at it that way, it's standard economic theory. It's probably even amenable to numerical analysis using analogues of elementary engineering design formulae. How much current will this circuit draw at an input voltage of 440V? What diameter of hydraulic hose, and hence what volume of oil, do I need for this hydraulic power press application? How many BTC do I need to maintain a gross throughput of $1million dollars a month in my remittance business to the Philippines? Or to India, where the velocity is less because of tougher regulation?

That value-of-utility is quite easily quantified, using this sort of approach, and after that it's everyday stuff for any competent finance director.</description>                            
