       			<item>
				<guid>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c043e5ecad048d4c02ec61</guid>
				<title>Krugman's evilisly bad tech predictions</title>
				<pubDate>Sun, 29 Dec 2013 10:46:45 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c043e5ecad048d4c02ec61</link>
				<description>Krugman, who predicted in 1998 that by 2005 the impact of the Internet on economy will be no greater than the fax machines :) - is now struggling to understand an other tech intrusion into economics: Bitcoin - and digital currencies.

In his stupidly titled blog entry in the New York Times he brings in to the discussion as a help for him, a fellow economist, Brad DeLong, who asks all the questions that Joe is asking here now.

The floor value of Bitcoin.

Krugman explains: &quot;Underpinning the value of the dollar is a combination of 
(a) the fact that you can use them to pay your taxes to the U.S. government, and 
(b) that the Federal Reserve is a potential dollar sink and has promised to buy them back and extinguish them if their real value starts to sink at (much) more than 2%/year (yes, I know).&quot;

Basically for Krugman the floor value of dollar is 
a) the government ability to collect taxes without receiving plenty of chickens, goats
b) the Federal Reserve promised to buy them back...

I am not sure how collecting tax gives value to a currency - it does not make it gold for sure.

The Federal Reserve buy back argument is interesting, considering that The Fed is privately owned entity - not a US government institution, as the name cunningly suggests.

I would be curious, how would The Fed buy back trillions of dollars if everybody wanted to get rid of it, because the value dropped more than 2%? And what would The Fed pay for the dollar? Gold? Does The Fed own enough gold to cover all the dollar it prints?

The floor value of Bitcoin is not centered around government tax collection and a private entity, which probably has no ability to do what it is promising.

The floor value of Bitcoin is that people around the world, have decided to accept Bitcoin to play the role of making payments for products and services among the members of the grass root, volunteer community - without the need of the assistance of any traditional third party (government, existing financial system, financial infrastructure).

The community is open for anyone, people or businesses can join and participate, regardless of their location, nationality.

Hell, even the government can join in and accept Bitcoin for collecting taxes - and do all government businesses in Bitcoin. 

I bet it would be much cheaper for taxpayers than what the government pays for financial services now. Not to mention that it would be completely transparent for tax payers where the government is spending their money.

I think these are much more solid floor value propositions than the US dollar ever offered.</description>                            
			</item>
