       			<item>
				<guid>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c034686da8118a0eda2055</guid>
				<title>Vitalik Buterin</title>
				<pubDate>Sun, 29 Dec 2013 09:40:40 -0500</pubDate>
				<link>http://www.businessinsider.com/c/52c034686da8118a0eda2055</link>
				<description>It seems to be a common psychological trait to want to have some kind of &quot;floor&quot; or certainty behind everything; indeed, I think that that is a major reason why many people support centralized and authoritarian institutions: they are the only kind of institutions that can provide that illusory perception of certainty, even if they actually just serve to shuffle risk over to catastrophic black swan events in the long term. In reality, however, that kind of thinking is fatally flawed; in the real world, there is no absolute certainty behind anything (even mathematics, since you can't trust your own mind to be 100% infallible). Gold seems to have a price floor because it is pretty, but the reality is that lots of things are pretty, including many ornaments you can buy in Chinatown for $1. Gold only has the elevated value because of (1) speculative / store-of-value investment, and (2) because it is a Veblen good - its specific kind of beauty is valued only because it is rare. If people stopped buying gold for investment reasons, gold would fall to $100, and everybody would start walking around with gold necklaces - making gold lose even more value since it's no longer that special and perhaps fall to $10. The US dollar has no price floor either; sure, the US government accepts them for taxes, but it does not accept them for taxes at any specific ratio. If the market value of a US dollar falls by a factor of 1000, the value of each dollar toward paying your income tax liability will also drop by 1000x - in fact, even more so, because in such a scenario everyone with even a losing business in real-value terms would have to pay tax on capital &quot;gains&quot; on the increased number of dollars that they have. There's also nothing technically guaranteeing that the US government will keep accepting US dollars. The Zimbabwean government doesn't accept its own currency. It's all a probabilities game.

See also: &lt;a href=&quot;http://bitcoinmagazine.com/8640/an-exploration-of-intrinsic-value-what-it-is-why-bitcoin-doesnt-have-it-and-why-bitcoin-does-have-it/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot; &gt;http://bitcoinmagazine.com/8640/an-exploration-of-intrinsic-value-what-it-is-why-bitcoin-doesnt-have-it-and-why-bitcoin-does-have-it/&lt;/a&gt;</description>                            
